# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wifi-mesh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] 802.11 are a set of IEEE standards that govern wireless networking transmission protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] They are commonly used today to provide wireless connectivity in the home, office and some commercial establishments.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] The IEEE 802.11s standard was issued in 2011 and was superseded in 2012 when it became part of the IEEE 802.11 standard that was issued in 2012.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] One or more routing protocols suitable to the actual network physical topology are required.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] 802.11s requires the Hybrid Wireless Mesh Protocol, or HWMP to be supported as a default.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] However, other mesh, ad hoc (Associativity-Based Routing, Zone Routing Protocol, and location based routing) or dynamic link-state routing (OLSR, B.A.T.M.A.N., OSPF) may be supported or even static routing (WDS).
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] A mesh often consists of many small nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] When mobile users or heavy loads are concerned, there will often be a handoff from one base station to another, and not only from 802.11 but from other (GSM, Bluetooth, PCS and other cordless phone) networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Accordingly, IEEE 802.21, which specifies this handoff between nodes both obeying 802.11s and otherwise, may be required.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] This is especially likely if a longer-range lower-bandwidth service is deployed to minimize mesh dead zones, e.g.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Mesh networking often involves network access by previously unknown parties, especially when a transient visitor population is being served.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Thus the accompanying IEEE 802.11u standard will be required by most mesh networks to authenticate these users without pre-registration or any prior offline communication.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] *Pre-standard captive portal approaches are also common.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] 802.11s started as a Study Group of IEEE 802.11 in September 2003.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] A call for proposals was issued in May 2005, which resulted in the submission of 15 proposals submitted to a vote in July 2005.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] After a series of eliminations and mergers, the proposals dwindled to two (the "SEE-Mesh" and "Wi-Mesh" proposals), which became a joint proposal in January 2006.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] This merged proposal was accepted as draft D0.01 after a unanimous confirmation vote in March 2006.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] The draft evolved through informal comment resolution until it was submitted for a Letter Ballot in November 2006 as Draft D1.00.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Draft D2.00 was submitted in March 2008 which failed with only 61% approval.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] A year was spent clarifying and pruning until Draft D3.00 was created which reached WG approval with 79% in March 2009.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] In June 2011 the fifth recirculation Sponsor Ballot, on TGs Draft 12.0, was closed.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] The 2012 release of the 802.11 specification (802.11-2012) directly incorporates Mesh Routing functionality.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] An 802.11s wireless mesh network device is labelled as Mesh Station (mesh STA), or simply an ad hoc node.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Mesh STAs form mesh links with one another, over which mesh paths can be established using an ad hoc mobile routing protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] A key aspect of this architecture is the presence of multi-hop wireless links and routing of packets through other nodes towards the destination node.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] 802.11s defines a default mandatory routing protocol (Hybrid Wireless Mesh Protocol, or HWMP), yet allows vendors to operate using alternate routing protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] HWMP is inspired by a combination of AODV (RFC 3561), which uses on-demand ad hoc routing approach and tree-based routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Examples of on-demand ad hoc routing are Dynamic Source Routing and Associativity-Based Routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] AODV route discovery and localized route repair approaches are identical to Associativity-based Routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Prior work has discussed and compared these various routing protocols in detail.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Mesh STAs are individual devices using mesh services to communicate with other devices in the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] They can also collocate with 802.11 Access Points (APs) and provide access to the mesh network to 802.11 stations (STAs), which have broad market availability.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Also, mesh STAs can collocate with an 802.11 portal that implements the role of a gateway and provides access to one or more non-802.11 networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] In both cases, 802.11s provides a proxy mechanism to provide addressing support for non-mesh 802 devices, allowing for end-points to be cognizant of external addresses.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] 802.11s also includes mechanisms to provide deterministic network access, a framework for congestion control and power save.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] There are no defined roles in a mesh – no clients and servers, no initiators and responders.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Security protocols used in a mesh must, therefore, be true peer-to-peer protocols where either side can initiate to the other or both sides can initiate simultaneously.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Between peers, 802.11s defines the secure password-based authentication and key establishment protocol Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE).
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] SAE is based on Diffie–Hellman key exchange using finite cyclic groups which can be a primary cyclic group or an elliptic curve.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] The problem with a Diffie–Hellman key exchange is that it does not have an authentication mechanism.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] So the resulting key is influenced by a pre-shared key and the MAC addresses of both peers to solve the authentication problem.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] When peers discover each other (and security is enabled) they take part in an SAE exchange.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] If SAE completes successfully, each peer knows the other party possesses the mesh password and, as a by-product of the SAE exchange, the two peers establish a cryptographically strong key.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] This key is used with the "Authenticated Mesh Peering Exchange" (AMPE) to establish a secure peering and derive a session key to protect mesh traffic, including routing traffic.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] The IEEE 802.11s amendment is supported by many products such as open80211s, OLPC.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] In open80211s smaller meshes of under 32 nodes are supported.
[src:wifi-mesh/ieee-802-11s] Some of the projects were based on earlier (draft) versions.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:wifi-mesh/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A **wireless ad hoc network** (**WANET**) or **mobile ad hoc network** (**MANET**) is a decentralized type of wireless network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network is ad hoc because it does not rely on a pre-existing infrastructure, such as routers or wireless access points.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Instead, each node participates in routing by forwarding data for other nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The determination of which nodes forward data is made dynamically on the basis of network connectivity and the routing algorithm in use.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such wireless networks lack the complexities of infrastructure setup and administration, enabling devices to create and join networks "on the fly".
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each device in a MANET is free to move independently in any direction, and will therefore change its links to other devices frequently.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each must forward traffic unrelated to its own use, and therefore be a router.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The primary challenge in building a MANET is equipping each device to continuously maintain the information required to properly route traffic.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such networks may operate by themselves or may be connected to the larger Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] They may contain one or multiple and different transceivers between nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This results in a highly dynamic, autonomous topology.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] MANETs usually have a routable networking environment on top of a link layer ad hoc network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The earliest wireless data network was called PRNET, the packet radio network, and was sponsored by Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) in the early 1970s.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] (BBN) and SRI International designed, built, and experimented with these earliest systems.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Experimenters included Robert Kahn, Jerry Burchfiel, and Ray Tomlinson.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Similar experiments took place in the amateur radio community with the x25 protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These early packet radio systems predated the Internet, and indeed were part of the motivation of the original Internet Protocol suite.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Later DARPA experiments included the Survivable Radio Network (SURAN) project, which took place in the 1980s.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A successor to these systems was fielded in the mid-1990s for the US Army, and later other nations, as the Near-term digital radio.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another third wave of academic and research activity started in the mid-1990s with the advent of inexpensive 802.11 radio cards for personal computers.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Current wireless ad hoc networks are designed primarily for military utility.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Problems with packet radios are: (1) bulky elements, (2) slow data rate, (3) unable to maintain links if mobility is high.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The project did not proceed much further until the early 1990s when wireless ad hoc networks were born.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The growth of laptops and 802.11/Wi-Fi wireless networking have made MANETs a popular research topic since the mid-1990s.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Many academic papers evaluate protocols and their abilities, assuming varying degrees of mobility within a bounded space, usually with all nodes within a few hops of each other.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Different protocols are then evaluated based on measures such as the packet drop rate, the overhead introduced by the routing protocol, end-to-end packet delays, network throughput, ability to scale, etc.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In the early 1990s, Charles Perkins from SUN Microsystems USA, and Chai Keong Toh from Cambridge University separately started to work on a different Internet, that of a wireless ad hoc network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Perkins was working on the dynamic addressing issues.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Toh worked on a new routing protocol, which was known as ABR – associativity-based routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Perkins eventually proposed DSDV – Destination Sequence Distance Vector routing, which was based on distributed distance vector routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Toh's proposal was an on-demand based routing, i.e. routes are discovered on-the-fly in real-time as and when needed.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] ABR was implemented successfully into Linux OS on Lucent WaveLAN 802.11a enabled laptops and a practical ad hoc mobile network was therefore proven to be possible in 1999.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another routing protocol known as AODV was subsequently introduced and later proven and implemented in 2005.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In 2007, David Johnson and Dave Maltz proposed DSR – Dynamic Source Routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Minimal configuration and quick deployment make ad hoc networks suitable for emergency situations like natural disasters or military conflicts.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The presence of dynamic and adaptive routing protocols enables ad hoc networks to be formed quickly.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A mobile ad hoc network (MANET) is a continuously self-configuring, self-organizing, infrastructure-less network of mobile devices connected without wires.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] It is sometimes known as "on-the-fly" networks or "spontaneous networks".
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] VANETs are used for communication between vehicles and roadside equipment.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Intelligent vehicular ad hoc networks (InVANETs) are a kind of artificial intelligence that helps vehicles to behave in intelligent manners during vehicle-to-vehicle collisions, accidents.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Vehicles are using radio waves to communicate with each other, creating communication networks instantly on-the-fly while vehicles move along roads.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] VANET needs to be secured with lightweight protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A SPAN leverages existing hardware (primarily Wi-Fi and Bluetooth) and software (protocols) in commercially available smartphones to create peer-to-peer networks without relying on cellular carrier networks, wireless access points, or traditional network infrastructure.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] SPANs differ from traditional hub and spoke networks, such as Wi-Fi Direct, in that they support multi-hop relays and there is no notion of a group leader so peers can join and leave at will without destroying the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Apple's iPhone with iOS version 7.0 and higher is capable of multi-peer ad hoc mesh networking.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Mesh networks take their name from the topology of the resultant network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In a fully connected mesh, each node is connected to every other node, forming a "mesh".
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A partial mesh, by contrast, has a topology in which some nodes are not connected to others, although this term is seldom in use.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks can take the form of a mesh networks or others.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A wireless ad hoc network does not have fixed topology, and its connectivity among nodes is totally dependent on the behavior of the devices, their mobility patterns, distance with each other, etc.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Hence, wireless mesh networks are a particular type of wireless ad hoc networks, with special emphasis on the resultant network topology.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] While some wireless mesh networks (particularly those within a home) have relatively infrequent mobility and thus infrequent link breaks, other more mobile mesh networks require frequent routing adjustments to account for lost links.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Military or tactical MANETs are used by military units with emphasis on data rate, real-time requirement, fast re-routing during mobility, data security, radio range, and integration with existing systems.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Common radio waveforms include the US Army's JTRS SRW and Silvus Technologies MN-MIMO Waveform (Mobile Networked MIMO),.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Ad hoc mobile communications come in well to fulfill this need, especially its infrastructureless nature, fast deployment, and operation.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Military MANETs are used by military units with an emphasis on rapid deployment, infrastructureless, all-wireless networks (no fixed radio towers), robustness (link breaks are no problem), security, range, and instant operation.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Flying ad hoc networks (FANETs) are composed of unmanned aerial vehicles, allowing great mobility and providing connectivity to remote areas.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Unmanned aerial vehicle, is an aircraft with no pilot on board.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] UAVs can be remotely controlled (i.e., flown by a pilot at a ground control station) or can fly autonomously based on pre-programmed flight plans.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Civilian usage of UAV include modeling 3D terrains, package delivery (Logistics), etc.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] UAVs have also been used by US Air Force for data collection and situation sensing, without risking the pilot in a foreign unfriendly environment.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With wireless ad hoc network technology embedded into the UAVs, multiple UAVs can communicate with each other and work as a team, collaboratively to complete a task and mission.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] If a UAV is destroyed by an enemy, its data can be quickly offloaded wirelessly to other neighboring UAVs.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The UAV ad hoc communication network is also sometimes referred to UAV instant sky network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] More generally, aerial MANET in UAVs are now (as of 2021) successfully implemented and operational as mini tactical reconnaissance ISR UAVs like the BRAMOR C4EYE from Slovenia.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Navy ships traditionally use satellite communications and other maritime radios to communicate with each other or with ground station back on land.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, such communications are restricted by delays and limited bandwidth.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks enable ship-area-networks to be formed while at sea, enabling high-speed wireless communications among ships, enhancing their sharing of imaging and multimedia data, and better co-ordination in battlefield operations.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some defense companies (such as Rockwell Collins, Silvus Technologies and Rohde & Schwartz) have produced products that enhance ship-to-ship and ship-to-shore communications.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Sensors are useful devices that collect information related to a specific parameter, such as noise, temperature, humidity, pressure, etc.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Sensors are increasingly connected via wireless to allow large-scale collection of sensor data.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a large sample of sensor data, analytics processing can be used to make sense out of these data.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The connectivity of wireless sensor networks rely on the principles behind wireless ad hoc networks, since sensors can now be deploy without any fixed radio towers, and they can now form networks on-the-fly.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Smart Dust" was one of the early projects done at U C Berkeley, where tiny radios were used to interconnect smart dust.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] More recently, mobile wireless sensor networks (MWSNs) have also become an area of academic interest.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Efforts have been made to co-ordinate and control a group of robots to undertake collaborative work to complete a task.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Centralized control is often based on a "star" approach, where robots take turns to talk to the controller station.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, with wireless ad hoc networks, robots can form a communication network on-the-fly, i.e., robots can now "talk" to each other and collaborate in a distributed fashion.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a network of robots, the robots can communicate among themselves, share local information, and distributively decide how to resolve a task in the most effective and efficient way.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another civilian use of wireless ad hoc network is for public safety.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At times of disasters (floods, storms, earthquakes, fires, etc.), a quick and instant wireless communication network is necessary.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Especially at times of earthquakes when radio towers had collapsed or were destroyed, wireless ad hoc networks can be formed independently.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Firefighters and rescue workers can use ad hoc networks to communicate and rescue those injured.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Commercial radios with such capability are available on the market.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks allow sensors, videos, instruments, and other devices to be deployed and interconnected wirelessly for clinic and hospital patient monitoring, doctor and nurses alert notification, and also making senses of such data quickly at fusion points, so that lives can be saved.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] MANETS can be used for facilitating the collection of sensor data for data mining for a variety of applications such as air pollution monitoring and different types of architectures can be used for such applications.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A key characteristic of such applications is that nearby sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires the techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] By measuring the spatial correlation between data sampled by different sensors, a wide class of specialized algorithms can be developed to develop more efficient spatial data mining algorithms as well as more efficient routing strategies.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Also, researchers have developed performance models for MANET to apply queueing theory.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Several books and works have revealed the technical and research challenges facing wireless ad hoc networks or MANETs.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The obvious appeal of MANETs is that the network is decentralised and nodes/devices are mobile, that is to say there is no fixed infrastructure which provides the possibility for numerous applications in different areas such as environmental monitoring, disaster relief and military communications.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since the early 2000s, interest in MANETs has greatly increased which, in part, is due to the fact mobility can improve network capacity, shown by Grossglauser and Tse along with the introduction of new technologies.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One main advantage to a decentralised network is that they are typically more robust than centralised networks due to the multi-hop fashion in which information is relayed.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] For example, in the cellular network setting, a drop in coverage occurs if a base station stops working, however the chance of a single point of failure in a MANET is reduced significantly since the data can take multiple paths.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since the MANET architecture evolves with time it has the potential to resolve issues such as isolation/disconnection from the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Further advantages of MANETS over networks with a fixed topology include flexibility (an ad hoc network can be created anywhere with mobile devices), scalability (adding nodes to the network is easy) and lower administration costs (no need to build an infrastructure first).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a time evolving network it is clear we should expect variations in network performance due to no fixed architecture (no fixed connections).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Finally, finding a model that accurately represents human mobility whilst remaining mathematically tractable remains an open problem due to the large range of factors that influence it.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some typical models used include the random walk, random waypoint and levy flight models.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks can operate over different types of radios.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] All radios use modulation to move information over a certain bandwidth of radio frequencies.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the need to move large amounts of information quickly over long distances, a MANET radio channel ideally has large bandwidth (e.g. amount of radio spectrum), lower frequencies, and higher power.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the desire to communicate with many other nodes ideally simultaneously, many channels are needed.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given radio spectrum is shared and regulated, there is less bandwidth available at lower frequencies.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Processing many radio channels requires many resources.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the need for mobility, small size and lower power consumption are very important.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Picking a MANET radio and modulation has many trade-offs; many start with the specific frequency and bandwidth they are allowed to use.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wi-Fi ad hoc uses the unlicensed ISM 2.4 GHz radios.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] They can also be used on 5.8 GHz radios.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The higher the frequency, such as those of 300 GHz, absorption of the signal will be more predominant.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Army tactical radios usually employ a variety of UHF and SHF radios, including those of VHF to provide a variety of communication modes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At the 800, 900, 1200, 1800 MHz range, cellular radios are predominant.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some cellular radios use ad hoc communications to extend cellular range to areas and devices not reachable by the cellular base station.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Next generation Wi-Fi known as 802.11ax provides low delay, high capacity (up to 10 Gbit/s) and low packet loss rate, offering 12 streams – 8 streams at 5 GHz and 4 streams at 2.4 GHz.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] IEEE 802.11ax uses 8x8 MU-MIMO, OFDMA, and 80 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Hence, 802.11ax has the ability to form high capacity Wi-Fi ad hoc networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At 60 GHz, there is another form of Wi-Fi known as WiGi – wireless gigabit.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This has the ability to offer up to 7 Gbit/s throughput.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Currently, WiGi is targeted to work with 5G cellular networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Circa 2020, the general consensus finds the 'best' modulation for moving information over higher frequency waves to be orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing, as used in 4G LTE, 5G, and Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The challenges affecting MANETs span from various layers of the OSI protocol stack.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The media access layer (MAC) has to be improved to resolve collisions and hidden terminal problems.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network layer routing protocol has to be improved to resolve dynamically changing network topologies and broken routes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The transport layer protocol has to be improved to handle lost or broken connections.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The session layer protocol has to deal with discovery of servers and services.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A major limitation with mobile nodes is that they have high mobility, causing links to be frequently broken and reestablished.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Moreover, the bandwidth of a wireless channel is also limited, and nodes operate on limited battery power, which will eventually be exhausted.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These factors make the design of a mobile ad hoc network challenging.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The cross-layer design deviates from the traditional network design approach in which each layer of the stack would be made to operate independently.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The modified transmission power will help that node to dynamically vary its propagation range at the physical layer.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This is because the propagation distance is always directly proportional to transmission power.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This information is passed from the physical layer to the network layer so that it can take optimal decisions in routing protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A major advantage of this protocol is that it allows access of information between physical layer and top layers (MAC and network layer).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some elements of the software stack were developed to allow code updates *in situ*, i.e., with the nodes embedded in their physical environment and without needing to bring the nodes back into the lab facility.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such software updating relied on epidemic mode of dissemination of information and had to be done both efficiently (few network transmissions) and fast.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Routing in wireless ad hoc networks or MANETs generally falls into three categories, namely: proactive routing, reactive routing, and hybrid routing.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocols maintains fresh lists of destinations and their routes by periodically distributing routing tables throughout the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] As in a fix net nodes maintain routing tables.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Distance-vector protocols are based on calculating the direction and distance to any link in a network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Direction" usually means the next hop address and the exit interface.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Distance" is a measure of the cost to reach a certain node.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The least cost route between any two nodes is the route with minimum distance.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each node maintains a vector (table) of minimum distance to every node.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The cost of reaching a destination is calculated using various route metrics.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] RIP uses the hop count of the destination whereas IGRP takes into account other information such as node delay and available bandwidth.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocol finds a route based on user and traffic demand by flooding the network with Route Request or Discovery packets.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, clustering can be used to limit flooding.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The latency incurred during route discovery is not significant compared to periodic route update exchanges by all nodes in the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Is a simple routing algorithm in which every incoming packet is sent through every outgoing link except the one it arrived on.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Flooding is used in bridging and in systems such as Usenet and peer-to-peer file sharing and as part of some routing protocols, including OSPF, DVMRP, and those used in wireless ad hoc networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocol combines the advantages of *proactive* and *reactive routing*.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The routing is initially established with some proactively prospected routes and then serves the demand from additionally activated nodes through reactive flooding.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The choice of one or the other method requires predetermination for typical cases.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Reaction to traffic demand depends on gradient of traffic volume.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Position-based routing methods use information on the exact locations of the nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This information is obtained for example via a GPS receiver.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Based on the exact location the best path between source and destination nodes can be determined.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Links are influenced by the node's resources (e.g., transmitter power, computing power and memory) and behavioral properties (e.g., reliability), as well as link properties (e.g. length-of-link and signal loss, interference and noise).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since links can be connected or disconnected at any time, a functioning network must be able to cope with this dynamic restructuring, preferably in a way that is timely, efficient, reliable, robust, and scalable.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network must allow any two nodes to communicate by relaying the information via other nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A "path" is a series of links that connects two nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Various routing methods use one or two paths between any two nodes; flooding methods use all or most of the available paths.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In most wireless ad hoc networks, the nodes compete for access to shared wireless medium, often resulting in collisions (interference).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Collisions can be handled using centralized scheduling or distributed contention access protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Using cooperative wireless communications improves immunity to interference by having the destination node combine self-interference and other-node interference to improve decoding of the desired signals.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One key problem in wireless ad hoc networks is foreseeing the variety of possible situations that can occur.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] As a result, modeling and simulation (M&S) using extensive parameter sweeping and what-if analysis becomes an extremely important paradigm for use in ad hoc networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One solution is the use of simulation tools like OPNET, NetSim or ns2.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) developed a Mobile Ad-Hoc Network emulation testbed, where algorithms and applications were subjected to representative wireless network conditions.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The testbed was based on a version of the "MANE" (Mobile Ad hoc Network Emulator) software originally developed by NRL.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The traditional model is the random geometric graph.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Early work included simulating ad hoc mobile networks on sparse and densely connected topologies.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Nodes are firstly scattered in a constrained physical space randomly.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each node then has a predefined fixed cell size (radio range).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A node is said to be connected to another node if this neighbor is within its radio range.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Nodes are then moved (migrated away) based on a random model, using random walk or brownian motion.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Different mobility and number of nodes present yield different route length and hence different number of multi-hops.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These are graphs consisting of a set of nodes placed according to a point process in some usually bounded subset of the n-dimensional plane, mutually coupled according to a Boolean probability mass function of their spatial separation (see e.g. unit disk graphs).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The connections between nodes may have different weights to model the difference in channel attenuations.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One can then study network observables (such as connectivity, centrality or the degree distribution) from a graph-theoretic perspective.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One can further study network protocols and algorithms to improve network throughput and fairness.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Most wireless ad hoc networks do not implement any network access control, leaving these networks vulnerable to resource consumption attacks where a malicious node injects packets into the network with the goal of depleting the resources of the nodes relaying the packets.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] To thwart or prevent such attacks, it was necessary to employ authentication mechanisms that ensure that only authorized nodes can inject traffic into the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Even with authentication, these networks are vulnerable to packet dropping or delaying attacks, whereby an intermediate node drops the packet or delays it, rather than promptly sending it to the next hop.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In a multicast and dynamic environment, establishing temporary 1:1 secure 'sessions' using PKI with every other node is not feasible (like is done with HTTPS, most VPNs, etc. at the transport layer).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Instead, a common solution is to use pre-shared keys for symmetric, authenticated encryption at the link layer, for example MACsec using AES-256-GCM.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With this method, every properly formatted packet received is authenticated then passed along for decryption or dropped.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] It also means the key(s) in each node must be changed more often and simultaneously (e.g. to avoid reusing an IV).
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Trust establishment and management in MANETs face challenges due to resource constraints and the complex interdependency of networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Researchers of trust management in MANET suggested that such complex interactions require a composite trust metric that captures aspects of communications and social networks, and corresponding trust measurement, trust distribution, and trust management schemes.
[src:wifi-mesh/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Continuous monitoring of every node within a MANET is necessary for trust and reliability but difficult because it by definition is dis-continuous, 2) it requires input from the node itself and 3) from its 'nearby' peers.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] A **routing protocol** specifies how routers communicate with each other to distribute information that enables them to select paths between nodes on a computer network.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Routers perform the traffic directing functions on the Internet; data packets are forwarded through the networks of the internet from router to router until they reach their destination computer.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Routing algorithms determine the specific choice of route.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Each router has a prior knowledge only of networks attached to it directly.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] A routing protocol shares this information first among immediate neighbors, and then throughout the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] This way, routers gain knowledge of the topology of the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] The ability of routing protocols to dynamically adjust to changing conditions such as disabled connections and components and route data around obstructions is what gives the Internet its fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Certain additional characteristics such as multilayer interfacing may also be employed as a means of distributing uncompromised networking gateways to authorized ports.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] This has the added benefit of preventing issues with routing protocol loops.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Many routing protocols are defined in technical standards documents called RFCs.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Interior gateway protocols (IGPs) exchange routing information within a single routing domain.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Exterior gateway protocols exchange routing information between autonomous systems.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Many software implementations exist for most of the common routing protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Examples of open-source applications are Bird Internet routing daemon, Quagga, GNU Zebra, OpenBGPD, OpenOSPFD, and XORP.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Some network certification courses distinguish between routing protocols and *routed* protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] A **routed protocol** is used to deliver application traffic.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] It provides appropriate addressing information in its internet layer or network layer to allow a packet to be forwarded from one network to another.
[src:wifi-mesh/routing-protocol] Examples of routed protocols are the Internet Protocol (IP) and Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses multiple parts of the IEEE 802 protocol family and is designed to work well with its wired sibling, Ethernet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Compatible devices can network through wireless access points with each other as well as with wired devices and the Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi are specified by various IEEE 802.11 protocol standards, with different radio technologies determining radio bands, maximum ranges, and speeds that may be achieved.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi most commonly uses the 2.4 gigahertz (120 mm) UHF and 5 gigahertz (60 mm) SHF radio bands, with the 6 gigahertz SHF band used in newer generations of the standard; these bands are subdivided into multiple channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Channels can be shared between networks, but, within range, only one transmitter can transmit on a channel at a time.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's radio bands work best for line-of-sight use.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Common obstructions, such as walls, pillars, home appliances, etc., may greatly reduce range, but this also helps minimize interference between different networks in crowded environments.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The range of an access point is about 20 m (66 ft) indoors, while some access points claim up to a 150 m (490 ft) range outdoors.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Hotspot coverage can be as small as a single room with walls that block radio waves or as large as many square kilometers using multiple overlapping access points with roaming permitted between them.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Over time, the speed and spectral efficiency of Wi-Fi has increased.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As of 2025, some versions of Wi-Fi, running on suitable hardware at close range, can achieve speeds of 23 Gbit/s (gigabit per second).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Federal Communications Commission released parts of the ISM bands for unlicensed use for communications in the United States.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These frequency bands include the same 2.4 GHz bands used by equipment such as microwave ovens, and are thus subject to interference.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 1991 in the city of Nieuwegein in the Netherlands, the NCR Corporation and AT&T invented the precursor to 802.11, intended for use in cashier systems, under the name WaveLAN.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] NCR's Vic Hayes, who held the chair of IEEE 802.11 for ten years, along with Bell Labs engineer Bruce Tuch, approached the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) to create a standard and were involved in designing the initial 802.11b and 802.11a specifications within the IEEE.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] They have both been subsequently inducted into the Wi-Fi NOW Hall of Fame.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 1989 in Australia, a team of scientists began working on wireless LAN technology.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A prototype test bed for a wireless local area network (WLAN) was developed in 1992 by a team of researchers from the Radiophysics Division of the CSIRO (Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation) in Australia, led by John O'Sullivan.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A patent for Wi-Fi was lodged by the CSIRO in 1992.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The first version of the 802.11 protocol was released in 1997, and provided up to 2 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This was updated in 1999 with 802.11b to permit 11 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 1999, the Wi-Fi Alliance formed as a trade association to hold the Wi-Fi trademark under which most IEEE 802.11 products are sold.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The major commercial breakthrough came with Apple Inc. adopting Wi-Fi for their iBook series of laptops in 1999.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] It was the first mass consumer product to offer Wi-Fi network connectivity, which was then branded by Apple as AirPort.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This was in collaboration with the same group that helped create the standard: Vic Hayes, Bruce Tuch, Cees Links, Rich McGinn, and others from Lucent.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2000, Radiata, a group of Australian scientists connected to the CSIRO, were the first to use the 802.11a standard on chips connected to a Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses a large number of patents held by multiple different organizations.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Australia, the United States and the Netherlands simultaneously claim the invention of Wi-Fi, and a consensus has not been reached globally.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2009, the Australian CSIRO was awarded $200 million after a patent settlement with 14 technology companies, with a further $220 million awarded in 2012 after legal proceedings with 23 companies.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2016, the CSIRO's WLAN prototype test bed was chosen as Australia's contribution to the exhibition *A History of the World in 100 Objects* held in the National Museum of Australia.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi*, commercially used as early as August 1999, was coined by the brand-consulting firm Interbrand.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance had hired Interbrand to create a name that was "a little catchier than 'IEEE 802.11b Direct Sequence'." According to Phil Belanger, a founding member of the Wi-Fi Alliance, the term *Wi-Fi* was chosen from a list of ten names that Interbrand proposed.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The yin-yang Wi-Fi logo indicates the certification of a product for interoperability.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The name is often written as *WiFi*, *Wifi*, or *wifi*, but these are not approved by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] IEEE, a separate but related organization, has stated "WiFi is a short name for Wireless Fidelity" on their website.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi* was partly chosen because it sounds similar to Hi-Fi, which consumers take to mean *high fidelity* or *high quality*.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Interbrand hoped consumers would find the name catchy, and that they would assume this *wireless* protocol has high fidelity because of its name.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Other technologies intended for fixed points, including Motorola Canopy, are usually called *fixed wireless*.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Alternative wireless technologies include Zigbee, Z-Wave, Bluetooth and mobile phone standards.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] To connect to a Wi-Fi LAN, a computer must be equipped with a wireless network interface controller.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The combination of a computer and an interface controller is called a *station*.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Stations are identified by one or more MAC addresses.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi nodes often operate in infrastructure mode in which all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] *Ad hoc mode* refers to devices communicating directly with each other, without communicating with an access point.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A service set is the set of all the devices associated with a particular Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Devices in a service set need not be on the same wavebands or channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A service set can be local, independent, extended, mesh, or a combination.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Each service set has an associated identifier, a 32-byte service set identifier (SSID), which identifies the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The SSID is configured within the devices that are part of the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A basic service set (BSS) is a group of stations that share the same wireless channel, SSID, and other settings that have wirelessly connected, usually to the same access point.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Each BSS is identified by a MAC address called the *BSSID*.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE does not test equipment for compliance with their standards.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance was formed in 1999 to establish and enforce standards for interoperability and backward compatibility, and to promote wireless local-area-network technology.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance enforces the use of the Wi-Fi brand to technologies based on the IEEE 802.11 standards from the IEEE.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Manufacturers with membership in the Wi-Fi Alliance, whose products pass the certification process, gain the right to mark those products with the Wi-Fi logo.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Specifically, the certification process requires conformance to the IEEE 802.11 radio standards, the WPA and WPA2 security standards, and the EAP authentication standard.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Certification may optionally include tests of IEEE 802.11 draft standards, interaction with cellular-phone technology in converged devices, and features relating to security set-up, multimedia, and power-saving.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Not every Wi-Fi device is submitted for certification.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The lack of Wi-Fi certification does not necessarily imply that a device is incompatible with other Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance may or may not sanction derivative terms, such as Super Wi-Fi, coined by the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to describe proposed networking in the UHF TV band in the US.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Equipment frequently supports multiple versions of Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] To communicate, devices must use a common Wi-Fi version.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The versions differ between the radio wavebands they operate on, the radio bandwidth they occupy, the maximum data rates they can support and other details.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Some versions permit the use of multiple antennas, which permits greater speeds as well as reduced interference.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Historically, the equipment listed the versions of Wi-Fi supported using the name of the IEEE standards.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance introduced simplified Wi-Fi generational numbering to indicate equipment that supports Wi-Fi 4 (802.11n), Wi-Fi 5 (802.11ac) and Wi-Fi 6 (802.11ax).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These generations have a high degree of backward compatibility with previous versions.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The alliance has stated that the generational level 4, 5, or 6 can be indicated in the user interface when connected, along with the signal strength.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi technology may be used to provide local network and Internet access to devices that are within Wi-Fi range of one or more routers that are connected to the Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The coverage of one or more interconnected access points can extend from an area as small as a few rooms to as large as many square kilometres.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Coverage in the larger area may require a group of access points with overlapping coverage.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For example, public outdoor Wi-Fi technology has been used successfully in wireless mesh networks in London.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi provides services in private homes, businesses, as well as in public spaces.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi hotspots may be set up either free of charge or commercially, often using a captive portal webpage for access.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Organizations, enthusiasts, authorities and businesses, such as airports, hotels, and restaurants, often provide free or paid-use hotspots to attract customers, to provide services to promote business in selected areas.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Routers often incorporate a digital subscriber line modem or a cable modem and a Wi-Fi access point, are frequently set up in homes and other buildings, to provide Internet access for the structure.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, battery-powered routers may include a mobile broadband modem and a Wi-Fi access point.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] When subscribed to a cellular data carrier, they allow nearby Wi-Fi stations to access the Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A number of smartphones have a built-in mobile hotspot capability of this sort, though carriers often disable the feature, or charge a separate fee to enable it.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Standalone devices such as MiFi- and WiBro-branded devices provide the capability.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Some laptops that have a cellular modem card can also act as mobile Internet Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Multiple traditional university campuses in the developed world provide at least partial Wi-Fi coverage.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Carnegie Mellon University built the first campus-wide wireless Internet network, called Wireless Andrew, at its Pittsburgh campus in 1993 before Wi-Fi branding existed.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A number of universities collaborate in providing Wi-Fi access to students and staff through the Eduroam international authentication infrastructure.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In the early 2000s, multiple cities around the world announced plans to construct citywide Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] There are a number of successful examples; in 2004, Mysore (Mysuru) became India's first Wi-Fi-enabled city.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A company called WiFiyNet has set up hotspots in Mysore, covering the whole city and a few nearby villages.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Cloud, Florida and Sunnyvale, California, became the first cities in the United States to offer citywide free Wi-Fi (from MetroFi).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Minneapolis has generated $1.2 million in profit annually for its provider.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In May 2010, the then London mayor Boris Johnson pledged to have London-wide Wi-Fi by 2012.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Several boroughs including Westminster and Islington already had extensive outdoor Wi-Fi coverage at that point.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] New York City announced a city-wide campaign to convert old phone booths into digital kiosks in 2014.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The project, titled LinkNYC, has created a network of kiosks that serve as public Wi-Fi hotspots, high-definition screens and landlines.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Installation of the screens began in late 2015.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The city government plans to implement more than seven thousand kiosks over time, eventually making LinkNYC the largest and fastest public, government-operated Wi-Fi network in the world.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The UK has planned a similar project across major cities of the country, with the project's first implementation in the London Borough of Camden.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Officials in South Korea's capital Seoul were moving to provide free Internet access at more than 10,000 locations around the city, including outdoor public spaces, major streets, and densely populated residential areas.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Seoul was planning to grant leases to KT, LG Telecom, and SK Telecom.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The companies were supposed to invest $44 million in the project, which was to be completed in 2015.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning systems use known positions of Wi-Fi hotspots to identify a device's location.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] It is used when GPS isn't suitable due to issues like signal interference or slow satellite acquisition.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This includes assisted GPS, urban hotspot databases, and indoor positioning systems.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning relies on measuring signal strength (RSSI) and fingerprinting.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Parameters like SSID and MAC address are crucial for identifying access points.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The accuracy depends on nearby access points in the database.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Signal fluctuations can cause errors, which can be reduced with noise-filtering techniques.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For low precision, integrating Wi-Fi data with geographical and time information has been proposed.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi RTT capability introduced in IEEE 802.11mc allows for positioning based on round trip time measurement, an improvement over the RSSI method.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE 802.11az standard promises further improvements in geolocation accuracy.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi sensing is used in applications such as motion detection and gesture recognition.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi stations communicate by sending each other data packets, blocks of data individually sent and delivered over radio on various channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As with all radio, this is done by the modulation and demodulation of carrier waves.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi use different techniques, 802.11b uses direct-sequence spread spectrum on a single carrier, whereas 802.11a, Wi-Fi 4, 5 and 6 use orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Channels are used half duplex and can be time-shared by multiple networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Any packet sent by one computer is locally received by stations tuned to that channel, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Stations typically ignore information not addressed to them.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The use of the same channel also means that the data bandwidth is shared, so for example, available throughput to each device is halved when two stations are actively transmitting.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, stations come programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] On the reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA) governs the way stations share channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] With CSMA/CA stations attempt to avoid collisions by beginning transmission only after the channel is sensed to be idle, but then transmit their packet data in its entirety.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] CSMA/CA cannot completely prevent collisions, as two stations may sense the channel to be idle at the same time and thus begin transmission simultaneously.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A collision happens when a station receives signals from multiple stations on a channel at the same time.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This corrupts the transmitted data and can require stations to re-transmit.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The lost data and re-transmission reduces throughput, in some cases severely.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The 802.11 standard provides several distinct radio frequency ranges for use in Wi-Fi communications: 900 MHz, 2.4 GHz, 3.6 GHz, 4.9 GHz, 5 GHz, 6 GHz and 60 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Each range is divided into a multitude of channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In the standards, channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing within a band (except in the 60 GHz band, where they are 2.16 GHz apart), and the number refers to the centre frequency of the channel.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Although channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing, transmitters generally occupy at least 20 MHz, and standards allow for neighbouring channels to be bonded together to form a wider channel for higher throughput.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Countries apply their own regulations to the allowable channels, allowed users and maximum power levels within these frequency ranges.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] 802.11b/g/n can use the 2.4 GHz band, operating in the United States under FCC Part 15 rules and regulations.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In this frequency band, equipment may occasionally suffer interference from microwave ovens, cordless telephones, USB 3.0 hubs, Bluetooth and other devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Spectrum assignments and operational limitations are not consistent worldwide: Australia and Europe allow for an additional two channels (12, 13) beyond the 11 permitted in the United States for the 2.4 GHz band, while Japan has three more (12–14).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] 802.11a/h/j/n/ac/ax can use the 5 GHz U-NII band, which, for much of the world, offers at least 23 non-overlapping 20 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This is in contrast to the 2.4 GHz frequency band where the channels are only 5 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In general, lower frequencies have longer range but have less capacity.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The 5 GHz bands are absorbed to a greater degree by common building materials than the 2.4 GHz bands and usually give a shorter range.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As 802.11 specifications evolved to support higher throughput, the protocols have become much more efficient in their bandwidth use.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Additionally, they have gained the ability to aggregate channels together to gain still more throughput where the bandwidth for additional channels is available.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n allows for double radio spectrum bandwidth (40 MHz) per channel compared to 802.11a or 802.11g (20 MHz).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n can be set to limit itself to 20 MHz bandwidth to prevent interference in dense communities.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In the 5 GHz band, 20 MHz, 40 MHz, 80 MHz, and 160 MHz channels are permitted with some restrictions, giving much faster connections.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi is part of the IEEE 802 protocol family.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The data is organized into 802.11 frames that are very similar to Ethernet frames at the data link layer, but with extra address fields.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] MAC addresses are used as network addresses for routing over the LAN.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's MAC and physical layer (PHY) specifications are defined by IEEE 802.11 for modulating and receiving one or more carrier waves to transmit the data in the infrared, and 2.4, 3.6, 5, 6, or 60 GHz frequency bands.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] They are created and maintained by the IEEE LAN/MAN Standards Committee (IEEE 802).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The base version of the standard was released in 1997 and has had many subsequent amendments.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The standard and amendments provide the basis for wireless network products using the Wi-Fi brand.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] While each amendment is officially revoked when incorporated in the latest version of the standard, the corporate world tends to market to the revisions because they concisely denote capabilities of their products.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As a result, in the market place, each revision tends to become its own standard.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In addition to 802.11, the IEEE 802 protocol family has specific provisions for Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These are required because Ethernet's cable-based media are not usually shared, whereas with wireless all transmissions are received by all stations within the range that employ that radio channel.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] While Ethernet has essentially negligible error rates, wireless communication media are subject to significant interference.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Therefore, the accurate transmission is not guaranteed so delivery is, therefore, a best-effort delivery mechanism.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Because of this, for Wi-Fi, the Logical Link Control (LLC) specified by IEEE 802.2 employs Wi-Fi's media access control (MAC) protocols to manage retries without relying on higher levels of the protocol stack.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For internetworking purposes, Wi-Fi is usually layered as a link layer below the internet layer of the Internet Protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This means that nodes have an associated internet address and, with suitable connectivity, this allows full Internet access.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In infrastructure mode, which is the most common mode used, all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi also allows communications directly from one computer to another without an access point intermediary.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This is called *ad hoc* Wi-Fi transmission.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Different types of ad hoc networks exist.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In the simplest case, network nodes must talk directly to each other.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In more complex protocols nodes may forward packets, and nodes keep track of how to reach other nodes, even if they move around.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Ad hoc mode was first described by Chai Keong Toh in his 1996 patent of wireless ad hoc routing, implemented on Lucent WaveLAN 802.11a wireless on IBM ThinkPads over a size nodes scenario spanning a region of over a mile.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The success was recorded in *Mobile Computing* magazine (1999) and later published formally in *IEEE Transactions on Wireless Communications*, 2002 and *ACM SIGMETRICS Performance Evaluation Review*, 2001.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This wireless ad hoc network mode has proven popular with multiplayer video games on handheld game consoles, such as the Nintendo DS and PlayStation Portable.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] It is also popular on digital cameras, and other consumer electronics devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Some devices can also share their Internet connection using ad hoc, becoming hotspots or virtual routers.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, the Wi-Fi Alliance promotes the specification Wi-Fi Direct for file transfers and media sharing through a new discovery and security methodology.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Another mode of direct communication over Wi-Fi is Tunneled Direct Link Setup (TDLS), which enables two devices on the same Wi-Fi network to communicate directly, instead of via the access point.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] An Extended Service Set may be formed by deploying multiple access points that are configured with the same SSID and security settings.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi client devices typically connect to the access point that can provide the strongest signal within that service set.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Increasing the number of Wi-Fi access points for a network provides redundancy, better range, support for fast handover, and increased overall network capacity by using more channels or by defining smaller cells.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Except for the smallest implementations (such as home or small office networks), Wi-Fi implementations have moved toward *thin* access points, with more of the network intelligence housed in a centralized network appliance, relegating individual access points to the role of dumb transceivers.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Outdoor applications may use mesh topologies.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi operational range depends on factors such as the frequency band, modulation technique, transmitter power output, receiver sensitivity, antenna gain and type, and propagation and interference characteristics in the environment.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] At longer distances, speed is typically reduced.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Compared to cell phones and similar technology, Wi-Fi transmitters are low-power devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In general, the maximum amount of power that a Wi-Fi device can transmit is limited by local regulations, such as FCC Part 15 in the US.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Equivalent isotropically radiated power (EIRP) in the European Union is limited to 20 dBm (100 mW).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi, however, has higher power compared to some other standards designed to support wireless personal area network applications.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For example, Bluetooth provides a much shorter propagation range between 1 and 100 metres (1 and 100 yards) and so in general has a lower power consumption.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Other low-power technologies such as Zigbee have fairly long range, but much lower data rate.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The high power consumption of Wi-Fi makes battery life in some mobile devices a concern.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] On wireless routers with detachable antennas, it is possible to improve range by fitting upgraded antennas.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] An access point compliant with either 802.11b or 802.11g, using the stock omnidirectional antenna might have a range of 0.1 km.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The same radio with an external semi-parabolic antenna (15 dB gain) with a similarly equipped receiver at the far end might have a range of over 32 km.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Higher gain rating (dBi) indicates deviation from a theoretical, perfect isotropic radiator toward a directional antenna, and therefore the antenna can project or accept a usable signal further in particular directions, as compared to a similar output power on a more isotropic antenna.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For example, an 8 dBi antenna used with a 100 mW driver has a similar horizontal range to a 6 dBi antenna being driven at 500 mW.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This assumes that radiation in the vertical direction is not useful for communications.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi 4 and higher standards allow devices to have multiple antennas on transmitters and receivers.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Multiple antennas enable the equipment to exploit multipath propagation on the same frequency bands, giving higher speeds and more than doubled range.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi 5 standard uses the 5 GHz band exclusively, and is capable of multi-station WLAN throughput of at least 1 gigabit per second, and a single station throughput of at least 500 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This standard uses several signal processing techniques such as multi-user MIMO and 4 × 4 spatial multiplexing streams, and wide channel bandwidth (160 MHz) to achieve its gigabit throughput.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] With Wi-Fi signals, line-of-sight usually works best, but signals can absorb, reflect, refract, diffract and fade through and around structures, both man-made and natural.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi signals are very strongly affected by metallic structures (including rebar in concrete, low-e coatings in glazing), rock structures (including marble) and water (such as found in vegetation).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Due to the complex nature of radio propagation at typical Wi-Fi frequencies, particularly around trees and buildings, algorithms can only approximately predict Wi-Fi signal strength for any given area in relation to a transmitter.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Performance associated with long-range Wi-Fi is more easily predicted, since longer links typically operate line-of-sight from towers that transmit above the surrounding foliage.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Distance records (using non-standard devices) include 382 km (237 mi) in June 2007, held by Ermanno Pietrosemoli and EsLaRed of Venezuela, transferring about 3 MB/sec of data between the mountain-tops of El Águila and Platillon.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The Swedish National Space Agency transferred data 420 km (260 mi), using 6 watt amplifiers to reach an overhead stratospheric balloon.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi connections can be blocked or the network throughput lowered by having other devices in the same area.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi protocols are designed to share the radio bandwidth reasonably fairly.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Nevertheless, Wi-Fi networks are still susceptible to the hidden node and exposed node problems.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A standard speed Wi-Fi signal occupies five channels in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Adjacent-channel interference can be caused by overlapping channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Any two channel numbers that differ by five or more, such as 2 and 7, do not overlap.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Channels 1, 6, and 11 are the only *group of three* non-overlapping channels in North America.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] However, whether the overlap is significant depends on physical spacing.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Channels that differ by four interfere a negligible amount – much less than reusing channels (which causes co-channel interference) – if transmitters are at least a few metres apart.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In Europe and Japan where channel 13 is available, using Channels 1, 5, 9, and 13 for 802.11g and 802.11n is viable and recommended.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] However, multiple 2.4 GHz 802.11b and 802.11g access points default to the same channel on initial startup, contributing to congestion on certain channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi pollution, or an excessive number of access points in the area, can prevent access and interfere with other devices' use of other access points, as well as decreasing overall signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These issues can become a problem in high-density areas, such as large apartment complexes or office buildings with multiple Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] It is also an issue when municipalities or other large entities (such as universities) seek to provide large area coverage.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Other devices use the 2.4 GHz band: microwave ovens, ISM band devices, security cameras, Zigbee devices, Bluetooth devices, video senders, cordless phones, baby monitors, and, in some countries, amateur radio, all of which can cause significant additional interference.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] On some 5 GHz bands interference from radar systems can occur in some places.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Access points that support those bands employ dynamic frequency selection, which listens for radar, and if detected, will not permit transmission on that band.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These bands can be used by low-power transmitters without a licence, and with few restrictions.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] However, while unintended interference is common, users who have been found to cause deliberate interference (particularly for attempting to locally monopolize these bands for commercial purposes) have been issued large fines.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Various layer-2 variants of IEEE 802.11 have different characteristics.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Across all flavours of 802.11, maximum achievable throughputs are either given based on measurements under ideal conditions or in the layer-2 data rates.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This, however, does not apply to typical deployments in which data are transferred between two endpoints, of which at least one is typically connected to a wired infrastructure.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This means that typically data frames pass an 802.11 (WLAN) medium and are converted to 802.3 (Ethernet) or vice versa.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Due to the difference in the frame (header) lengths of these two media, the packet size of an application determines the speed of the data transfer.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This means that an application that uses small packets (e.g., VoIP) creates a data flow with higher overhead and lower information rate.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Other factors that contribute to the overall application data rate include the energy with which the wireless signal is received.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The latter is determined by distance and by the configured output power of the communicating devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi allows wireless deployment of local area networks (LANs).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Also, spaces where cables cannot be run, such as outdoor areas and historical buildings, can host wireless LANs.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] However, building walls of certain materials, such as stone with high metal content, can block Wi-Fi signals.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A Wi-Fi device is a short-range wireless device.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi devices are fabricated on RF CMOS integrated circuit (RF circuit) chips.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Since the early 2000s, manufacturers are building wireless network adapters into most laptops.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The price of chipsets for Wi-Fi continues to drop, making it an economical networking option included in ever more devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Different competitive brands of access points and client network-interfaces can inter-operate at a basic level of service.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Products designated as "Wi-Fi Certified" by the Wi-Fi Alliance are backward compatible.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Unlike mobile phones, any standard Wi-Fi device works anywhere in the world.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A wireless access point (WAP) connects a group of wireless devices to an adjacent wired LAN.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] An access point resembles a network hub, relaying data between connected wireless devices in addition to a (usually) single connected wired device, most often an Ethernet hub or switch, allowing wireless devices to communicate with other wired devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless adapters allow devices to connect to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These adapters connect to devices using various external or internal interconnects such as mini PCIe (mPCIe, M.2), USB, ExpressCard and previously PCI, Cardbus, and PC Card.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] As of 2010, most newer laptop computers come equipped with built-in internal adapters.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless routers integrate a Wireless Access Point, Ethernet switch, and internal router firmware application that provides IP routing, NAT, and DNS forwarding through an integrated WAN-interface.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows wired and wireless Ethernet LAN devices to connect to a (usually) single WAN device such as a cable modem, DSL modem, or optical modem.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows all three devices, mainly the access point and router, to be configured through one central utility.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This utility is usually an integrated web server that is accessible to wired and wireless LAN clients and often optionally to WAN clients.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This utility may also be an application that is run on a computer, as is the case with as Apple's AirPort, which is managed with the AirPort Utility on macOS and iOS.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless network bridges can act to connect two networks to form a single network at the data-link layer over Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The main standard is the wireless distribution system (WDS).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless bridging can connect a wired network to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A bridge differs from an access point: an access point typically connects wireless devices to one wired network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A dual-band wireless bridge can also be used to enable 5 GHz wireless network operation on a device that only supports 2.4 GHz wireless and has a wired Ethernet port.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless range-extenders or wireless repeaters can extend the range of an existing wireless network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Strategically placed range-extenders can elongate a signal area or allow for the signal area to reach around barriers such as those pertaining in L-shaped corridors.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wireless devices connected through repeaters suffer from an increased latency for each hop, and there may be a reduction in the maximum available data throughput.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Besides, the effect of additional users using a network employing wireless range-extenders is to consume the available bandwidth faster than would be the case whereby a single user migrates around a network employing extenders.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For this reason, wireless range-extenders work best in networks supporting low traffic throughput requirements, such as for cases whereby a single user with a Wi-Fi-equipped tablet migrates around the combined extended and non-extended portions of the total connected network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Also, a wireless device connected to any of the repeaters in the chain has data throughput limited by the "weakest link" in the chain between the connection origin and connection end.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Networks using wireless extenders are more prone to degradation from interference from neighbouring access points that border portions of the extended network and that happen to occupy the same channel as the extended network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The security standard, Wi-Fi Protected Setup, allows embedded devices with a limited graphical user interface to connect to the Internet with ease.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Setup has 2 configurations: The Push Button configuration and the PIN configuration.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These embedded devices are also called The Internet of things and are low-power, battery-operated embedded systems.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Several Wi-Fi manufacturers design chips and modules for embedded Wi-Fi, such as GainSpan.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Increasingly in the last few years (particularly as of 2007), embedded Wi-Fi modules have become available that incorporate a real-time operating system and provide a simple means of wirelessly enabling any device that can communicate via a serial port.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This allows the design of simple monitoring devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] An example is a portable ECG device monitoring a patient at home.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] This Wi-Fi-enabled device can communicate via the Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These Wi-Fi modules are designed by OEMs so that implementers need only minimal Wi-Fi knowledge to provide Wi-Fi connectivity for their products.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In June 2014, Texas Instruments introduced the first ARM Cortex-M4 microcontroller with an onboard dedicated Wi-Fi MCU, the SimpleLink CC3200.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] It makes embedded systems with Wi-Fi connectivity possible to build as single-chip devices, which reduces their cost and minimum size, making it more practical to build wireless-networked controllers into inexpensive ordinary objects.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The main issue with wireless network security is its simplified access to the network compared to traditional wired networks such as Ethernet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] With wired networking, one must either gain access to a building (physically connecting into the internal network), or break through an external firewall.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] To access Wi-Fi, one must merely be within the range of the Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Most business networks protect sensitive data and systems by attempting to disallow external access.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Enabling wireless connectivity reduces security if the network uses inadequate or no encryption.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] An attacker who has gained access to a Wi-Fi network router can initiate a DNS spoofing attack against any other user of the network by forging a response before the queried DNS server has a chance to reply.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A common measure to deter unauthorized users involves hiding the access point's name by disabling the SSID broadcast.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] While effective against the casual user, it is ineffective as a security method because the SSID is broadcast in the clear in response to a client SSID query.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Another method is to only allow computers with known MAC addresses to join the network, but determined eavesdroppers may be able to join the network by spoofing an authorized address.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) encryption was designed to protect against casual snooping but it is no longer considered secure.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Tools such as AirSnort or Aircrack-ng can quickly recover WEP encryption keys.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Because of WEP's weakness the Wi-Fi Alliance approved Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) which uses TKIP.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] WPA was specifically designed to work with older equipment usually through a firmware upgrade.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Though more secure than WEP, WPA has known vulnerabilities.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The more secure WPA2 using Advanced Encryption Standard was introduced in 2004 and is supported by most new Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2017, a flaw in the WPA2 protocol was discovered, allowing a key replay attack, known as KRACK.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A flaw in a feature added to Wi-Fi in 2007, called Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS), let WPA and WPA2 security be bypassed.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The only remedy as of 2011 was to turn off Wi-Fi Protected Setup, which is not always possible.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Virtual private networks can be used to improve the confidentiality of data carried through Wi-Fi networks, especially public Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A URI using the Wi-Fi scheme can specify the SSID, encryption type, password/passphrase, and if the SSID is hidden or not, so users can follow links from QR codes, for instance, to join networks without having to manually enter the data.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A MeCard-like format is supported by Android and iOS 11+.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi access points typically default to an encryption-free (*open*) mode.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Novice users benefit from a zero-configuration device that works out-of-the-box, but this default does not enable any wireless security, providing open wireless access to a LAN.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] To turn security on requires the user to configure the device, usually via a software graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] On unencrypted Wi-Fi networks connecting devices can monitor and record data (including personal information).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Such networks can only be secured by using other means of protection, such as a VPN, or Hypertext Transfer Protocol over Transport Layer Security (HTTPS).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The older wireless-encryption standard, Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), has been shown easily breakable even when correctly configured.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) encryption, which became available in devices in 2003, aimed to solve this problem.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) ratified in 2004 is considered secure, provided a strong passphrase is used.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] The 2003 version of WPA has not been considered secure since it was superseded by WPA2 in 2004.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, WPA3 was announced as a replacement for WPA2, increasing security; it rolled out on 26 June.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking refers to access to a wireless Internet connection by bringing one's computer within the range of another's wireless connection, and using that service without the subscriber's explicit permission or knowledge.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] During the early popular adoption of 802.11, providing open access points for anyone within range to use was encouraged to cultivate wireless community networks, particularly since people on average use only a fraction of their downstream bandwidth at any given time.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Recreational logging and mapping of other people's access points have become known as wardriving.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Indeed, many access points are intentionally installed without security turned on so that they can be used as a free service.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Providing access to one's Internet connection in this fashion may breach the Terms of Service or contract with the Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] These activities do not result in sanctions in most jurisdictions; however, legislation and case law differ considerably across the world.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A proposal to leave graffiti describing available services was called warchalking.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking often occurs unintentionally – a technically unfamiliar user might not change the default "unsecured" settings to their access point and operating systems can be configured to connect automatically to any available wireless network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] A user who happens to start up a laptop in the vicinity of an access point may find the computer has joined the network without any visible indication.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] Moreover, a user intending to join one network may instead end up on another one if the latter has a stronger signal.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] In combination with automatic discovery of other network resources (see DHCP and Zeroconf) this could lead wireless users to send sensitive data to the wrong middle-man when seeking a destination (see man-in-the-middle attack).
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p01] For example, a user could inadvertently use an unsecured network to log into a website, thereby making the login credentials available to anyone listening, if the website uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP without TLS.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Wireless Internet access has become much more embedded in society.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] It has thus changed how the society functions in a number of ways.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] As of 2017 over half the world did not have access to the Internet, prominently rural areas in developing nations.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Technology that has been implemented in more developed nations is often costly and energy inefficient.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] This has led to developing nations using more low-tech networks, frequently implementing renewable power sources that can solely be maintained through solar power, creating a network that is resistant to disruptions such as power outages.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] For instance, in 2007, a 450-kilometre (280 mi) network between Cabo Pantoja and Iquitos in Peru was erected in which all equipment is powered only by solar panels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] These long-range Wi-Fi networks have two main uses: offer Internet access to populations in isolated villages, and to provide healthcare to isolated communities.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] In the case of the latter example, it connects the central hospital in Iquitos to 15 medical outposts which are intended for remote diagnosis.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Access to Wi-Fi in public spaces such as cafés or parks allows people, in particular freelancers, to work remotely.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] While the accessibility of Wi-Fi is the strongest factor when choosing a place to work (75% of people would choose a place that provides Wi-Fi over one that does not), other factors influence the choice of specific hotspots.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] These vary from the accessibility of other resources, like books, the location of the workplace, and the social aspect of meeting other people in the same place.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Moreover, the increase of people working from public places results in more customers for local businesses thus providing an economic stimulus to the area.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, in the same study it has been noted that wireless connection provides more freedom of movement while working.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Both when working at home or from the office it allows the displacement between different rooms or areas.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] In some offices (notably Cisco offices in New York) the employees do not have assigned desks but can work from any office connecting their laptop to Wi-Fi hotspot.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] The Internet has become an integral part of living.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] As of 2016, 81.9% of American households have Internet access.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, 89% of American households with broadband connect via wireless technologies.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] 72.9% of American households have Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Wi-Fi networks have also affected how the interior of homes and hotels are arranged.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] For instance, architects have described that their clients no longer wanted only one room as their home office, but would like to work near the fireplace or have the possibility to work in different rooms.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] This contradicts architect's pre-existing ideas of the use of rooms that they designed.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, some hotels have noted that guests prefer to stay in certain rooms since they receive a stronger Wi-Fi signal.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] The World Health Organization (WHO) says, "no health effects are expected from exposure to RF fields from base stations and wireless networks", but notes that they promote research into effects from other RF sources.
[src:wifi-mesh/wi-fi-p02] The United Kingdom's Health Protection Agency reported in 2007 that exposure to Wi-Fi for a year results in the "same amount of radiation from a 20-minute mobile phone call".
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A **wireless mesh network** (**WMN**) is a communications network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A **mesh** refers to rich interconnection among devices or nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks often consist of mesh clients, mesh routers and gateways.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] If nodes constantly or frequently move, the mesh spends more time updating routes than delivering data.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] In a wireless mesh network, topology tends to be more static, so that routes computation can converge and delivery of data to their destinations can occur.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Hence, this is a low-mobility centralized form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Also, because it sometimes relies on static nodes to act as gateways, it is not a truly all-wireless ad hoc network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh clients are often laptops, cell phones, and other wireless devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh routers forward traffic to and from the gateways, which may or may not be connected to the Internet.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The coverage area of all radio nodes working as a single network is sometimes called a mesh cloud.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Access to this mesh cloud depends on the radio nodes working together to create a radio network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A mesh network is reliable and offers redundancy.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] When one node can no longer operate, the rest of the nodes can still communicate with each other, directly or through one or more intermediate nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks can self form and self heal.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks work with different wireless technologies including 802.11, 802.15, 802.16, cellular technologies and need not be restricted to any one technology or protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh radio networks were originally developed for military applications, such that every node could dynamically serve as a router for every other node.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] In that way, even in the event of a failure of some nodes, the remaining nodes could continue to communicate with each other, and, if necessary, serve as uplinks for the other nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Early wireless mesh network nodes had a single half-duplex radio that, at any one instant, could either transmit or receive, but not both at the same time.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This was accompanied by the development of shared mesh networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This was subsequently superseded by more complex radio hardware that could receive packets from an upstream node and transmit packets to a downstream node simultaneously (on a different frequency or a different CDMA channel).
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This allowed the development of switched mesh networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] As the size, cost, and power requirements of radios declined further, nodes could be cost-effectively equipped with multiple radios.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This, in turn, permitted each radio to handle a different function, for instance, one radio for client access, and another for backhaul services.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Work in this field has been aided by the use of game theory methods to analyze strategies for the allocation of resources and routing of packets.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh architecture is a first step towards providing cost effective and low mobility over a specific coverage area.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh infrastructure is, in effect, a network of routers minus the cabling between nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] It is built of peer radio devices that do not have to be cabled to a wired port like traditional WLAN access points (AP) do.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh infrastructure carries data over large distances by splitting the distance into a series of short hops.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Intermediate nodes not only boost the signal, but cooperatively pass data from point A to point B by making forwarding decisions based on their knowledge of the network, i.e. perform routing by first deriving the topology of the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks is a relatively "stable-topology" network except for the occasional failure of nodes or addition of new nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The path of traffic, being aggregated from a large number of end users, changes infrequently.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Practically all the traffic in an infrastructure mesh network is either forwarded to or from a gateway, while in wireless ad hoc networks or client mesh networks the traffic flows between arbitrary pairs of nodes.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] If rate of mobility among nodes are high, i.e., link breaks happen frequently, wireless mesh networks start to break down and have low communication performance.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This type of infrastructure can be decentralized (with no central server) or centrally managed (with a central server).
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Both are relatively inexpensive, and can be very reliable and resilient, as each node needs only transmit as far as the next node.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Nodes act as routers to transmit data from nearby nodes to peers that are too far away to reach in a single hop, resulting in a network that can span larger distances.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The topology of a mesh network must be relatively stable, i.e., not too much mobility.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] If one node drops out of the network, due to hardware failure or any other reason, its neighbors can quickly find another route using a routing protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh networks may involve either fixed or mobile devices.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] An important possible application for wireless mesh networks is VoIP.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] By using a quality of service scheme, the wireless mesh may support routing local telephone calls through the mesh.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Most applications in wireless mesh networks are similar to those in wireless ad hoc networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The principle is similar to the way packets travel around the wired Internet – data hops from one device to another until it eventually reaches its destination.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Dynamic routing algorithms implemented in each device allow this to happen.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] To implement such dynamic routing protocols, each device needs to communicate routing information to other devices in the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Each device then determines what to do with the data it receives – either pass it on to the next device or keep it, depending on the protocol.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The routing algorithm used should attempt to always ensure that the data takes the most appropriate (fastest) route to its destination.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Multi-radio mesh refers to having different radios operating at different frequencies to interconnect nodes in a mesh.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This means there is a unique frequency used for each wireless hop and thus a dedicated CSMA collision domain.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] With more radio bands, communication throughput is likely to increase as a result of more available communication channels.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This is similar to providing dual or multiple radio paths to transmit and receive data.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] technologies is further investigated, since their complexity and cost are still too high for wide commercialization.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Tremendous efforts on research of frequency-agile techniques are being performed for increased efficiency.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Cross-layer research is a popular current research topic where information is shared between different communications layers to increase the knowledge and current state of the network.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] This could facilitate development of new and more efficient protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A joint protocol that addresses various design problems—routing, scheduling, channel assignment etc.—can achieve higher performance since these problems are strongly co-related.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Note that careless cross-layer design can lead to code that is difficult to maintain and extend.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] a new SDN architecture for WMNs is explored that eliminates the need for multi-hop flooding of route information and therefore enables WMNs to easily expand.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The key idea is to split network control and data forwarding by using two separate frequency bands.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The forwarding nodes and the SDN controller exchange link-state information and other network control signaling in one of the bands, while actual data forwarding takes place in the other band.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A WMN can be seen as a group of nodes (clients or routers) that cooperate to provide connectivity.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] , where clients serve as routers to forward data packets, is exposed to many types of attacks that can interrupt the whole network and cause denial of service (DoS) or Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS).
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A number of wireless community networks have been started as grassroots projects across the world at various points in time.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] There are more than 70 competing schemes for routing packets across mesh networks.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] The IEEE has developed a set of standards under the title 802.11s.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] A less thorough list can be found at list of ad hoc routing protocols.
[src:wifi-mesh/wireless-mesh-network] Standard autoconfiguration protocols, such as DHCP or IPv6 stateless autoconfiguration may be used over mesh networks.
